Once your data is loaded into Python, you can display the first rows of your DataFrame by calling the .head(n=5) method, where n=5 indicates that you want to print the first five rows of your DataFrame.</p>
<p>In this exercise, you will read in a time series dataset that contains the number of "great" inventions and scientific discoveries from 1860 to 1959, and display its first five rows.</p>

<blockquote><p><strong>Test whether your data is of the correct type</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>When working with time series data in pandas, any date information should be formatted as a datetime64 type. Therefore, it is important to check that the columns containing the date information are of the correct type. You can check the type of each column in a DataFrame by using the .dtypes attribute. Fortunately, if your date columns come as strings, epochs, etcâ€¦ you can use the to_datetime() function to convert them to the appropriate datetime64 type:df['date_column'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date_column'])In this exercise, you will learn how to check the data type of the columns in your time series data and convert a date column to the appropriate datetime type.</p>
<p>Instructions: <br></p>

</ul>

<blockquote><p><strong>Your first plot!</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Let's take everything you have learned so far and plot your first time series plot. You will set the groundwork by producing a time series plot of your data and labeling the axes of your plot, as this makes the plot more readable and interpretable for the intended audience.</p>
<p>matplotlib is the most widely used plotting library in Python, and would be the most appropriate tool for this job. Fortunately for us, the pandas library has implemented a .plot() method on Series and DataFrame objects that is a wrapper around matplotlib.pyplot.plot(), which makes it easier to produce plots.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>

<blockquote><p><strong>Specify plot styles</strong></p>

<p>The matplotlib library also comes with a number of built-in stylesheets that allow you to customize the appearance of your plots. To use a particular style sheet for your plots, you can use the command plt.style.use(your_stylesheet) where your_stylesheet is the name of the style sheet.</p>
<p>In order to see the list of available style sheets that can be used, you can use the command print(plt.style.available). For the rest of this course, we will use the awesome fivethirtyeight style sheet.</p>

<blockquote><p><strong>Display and label plots</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>As you saw earlier, if the index of a pandas DataFrame consists of dates, then pandas will automatically format the x-axis in a human-readable way. In addition the .plot() method allows you to specify various other parameters to tailor your time series plot (color of the lines, width of the lines and figure size).</p>
<p>You may have noticed the use of the notation ax = df.plot(...) and wondered about the purpose of the ax object. This is because the plot function returns a matplotlib AxesSubplot object, and it is common practice to assign this returned object to a variable called ax. Doing so also allows you to include additional notations and specifications to your plot such as axis labels.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Specify the color of the line as 'blue'.</li>
<li>Width of the line as 2.</li>
<li>The dimensions of your plot to be of length 8 and width 3.</li>
<li>Specify the fontsize of 6.</li>
</ul>

</div>

<h3 id="Customize-your-time-series-plot">Customize your time series plot<a class="anchor-link" href="#Customize-your-time-series-plot"> </a></h3>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Subset time series data</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>When plotting time series data, you may occasionally want to visualize only a subset of the data. The pandas library provides powerful indexing and subsetting methods that allow you to extract specific portions of a DataFrame. For example, you can subset all the data between 1950 and 1960 in the discoveries DataFrame by specifying the following date range:<br></p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><span></span><span class="n">subset_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">discoveries</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;1950-01-01&#39;</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="s1">&#39;1960-01-01&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>
<p>Note: Subsetting your data this way is only possible if the index of your DataFrame contains dates of the datetime type. Failing that, the pandas library will return an error message.</p>
<p>Instructions<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Use discoveries to create a new DataFrame discoveries_subset_1 that contains all the data between January 1, 1945 and January 1, 1950.</li>
<li>Plot the time series of discoveries_subset_1 using a "blue" line plot.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">discoveries_subset_1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">discoveries</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;1945&#39;</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="s1">&#39;1950&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot the time series in your DataFrame as a blue area chart</span>
<span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">discoveries_subset_1</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;blue&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">)</span>

<h3 id="Plot-aggregates-of-your-data">Plot aggregates of your data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Plot-aggregates-of-your-data"> </a></h3><blockquote><p><strong>Display rolling averages</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>It is also possible to visualize rolling averages of the values in your time series. This is equivalent to "smoothing" your data, and can be particularly useful when your time series contains a lot of noise or outliers. For a given DataFrame df, you can obtain the rolling average of the time series by using the command:<br><code>python
df_mean = df.rolling(window=12).mean()</code>
<br>
The window parameter should be set according to the granularity of your time series. For example, if your time series contains daily data and you are looking for rolling values over a whole year, you should specify the parameter to window=365. In addition, it is easy to get rolling values for other other metrics, such as the standard deviation (.std()) or variance (.var()).</p>
<p>Instructions: <br></p>

<li>Plot the line chart of ma.</li>

df_by_year = df.groupby(index_year).mean()</code></pre>

<h2 id="Seasonality,-Trend-and-Noise">Seasonality, Trend and Noise<a class="anchor-link" href="#Seasonality,-Trend-and-Noise"> </a></h2><blockquote><p>You will go beyond summary statistics by learning about autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation plots. You will also learn how to automatically detect seasonality, trend and noise in your time series data.</p>

<h3 id="Autocorrelation-and-Partial-autocorrelation">Autocorrelation and Partial autocorrelation<a class="anchor-link" href="#Autocorrelation-and-Partial-autocorrelation"> </a></h3><blockquote><p><strong>Autocorrelation in time series data</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In the field of time series analysis, autocorrelation refers to the correlation of a time series with a lagged version of itself. For example, an autocorrelation of order 3 returns the correlation between a time series and its own values lagged by 3 time points.</p>
<p>It is common to use the autocorrelation (ACF) plot, also known as self-autocorrelation, to visualize the autocorrelation of a time-series. The plot_acf() function in the statsmodels library can be used to measure and plot the autocorrelation of a time series.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import tsaplots from statsmodels.graphics.</li>
<li>Use the plot_acf() function from tsaplots to plot the autocorrelation of the 'co2' column in co2_levels.</li>
<li>Specify a maximum lag of 24.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">style</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">use</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;fivethirtyeight&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.graphics</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">tsaplots</span>

<span class="n">fig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">tsaplots</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_acf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">co2_levels</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;co2&#39;</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">lags</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">24</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>

<p>Autocorrelation plots can be used to quickly discover patterns into your time series, so let's delve a little bit deeper into that!</p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Interpret autocorrelation plots</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>If autocorrelation values are close to 0, then values between consecutive observations are not correlated with one another. Inversely, autocorrelations values close to 1 or -1 indicate that there exists strong positive or negative correlations between consecutive observations, respectively.</p>
<p>In order to help you asses how trustworthy these autocorrelation values are, the plot_acf() function also returns confidence intervals (represented as blue shaded regions). If an autocorrelation value goes beyond the confidence interval region, you can assume that the observed autocorrelation value is statistically significant.</p>
<p>In the autocorrelation plot below, are consecutive observations highly correlated (i.e superior to 0.5) and statistically significant?</p>
<p><img src="https://assets.datacamp.com/production/course_5226/datasets/ch3_acf.png" alt="alt text"></p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p>Answer:They are highly correlated and statistically significant.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Partial autocorrelation in time series data</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Like autocorrelation, the partial autocorrelation function (PACF) measures the correlation coefficient between a time-series and lagged versions of itself. However, it extends upon this idea by also removing the effect of previous time points. For example, a partial autocorrelation function of order 3 returns the correlation between our time series (t_1, t_2, t_3, â€¦) and its own values lagged by 3 time points (t_4, t_5, t_6, â€¦), but only after removing all effects attributable to lags 1 and 2.</p>
<p>The <code>plot_pacf()</code> function in the statsmodels library can be used to measure and plot the partial autocorrelation of a time series.</p>
<p>Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import tsaplots from statsmodels.graphics.</li>
<li>Use the plot_pacf() function from tsaplots to plot the partial autocorrelation of the 'co2' column in co2_levels.</li>
<li>Specify a maximum lag of 24.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>

<h3 id="Seasonality,-trend-and-noise-in-time-series-data">Seasonality, trend and noise in time series data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Seasonality,-trend-and-noise-in-time-series-data"> </a></h3><blockquote><p><strong>Time series decomposition</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>When visualizing time series data, you should look out for some distinguishable patterns:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>seasonality: does the data display a clear periodic pattern?</li>
<li>trend: does the data follow a consistent upwards or downward slope?</li>
<li>noise: are there any outlier points or missing values that are not consistent with the rest of the data?
<br>
You can rely on a method known as time-series decomposition to automatically extract and quantify the structure of time-series data. The statsmodels library provides the seasonal_decompose() function to perform time series decomposition out of the box.<br><div class="highlight"><pre><span></span><span class="n">decomposition</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tsa</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">seasonal_decompose</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">time_series</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
<br>
You can extract a specific component, for example seasonality, by accessing the seasonal attribute of the decomposition object.</li>
</ul>
<p>Instructions: <br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import statsmodels.api using the alias sm.</li>
<li>Perform time series decomposition on the co2_levels DataFrame into a variable called decomposition.</li>
<li>Print the seasonality component of your time series decomposition.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
